						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">DRW wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">You can even declare<br /><tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">int a = 5;<br />int *b = &amp;a;</tt><br />and then call <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">b[3]</tt> and the compiler will not complain</div><br />That's <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undefined_behavior" class="postlink">undefined behavior</a>. An executable compiled from a program including this can do literally anything and the compiler will still conform to the standard. Though the standard does not require a diagnostic for all unspecified or undefined behaviors, a compiler ought to at least warn for an undefined behavior as easy to spot statically as this.</div>

